<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-178-602  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 178 602.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC-Computing  March 1990 v3 n3 p54(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>See the U.S.A. (electronic atlas and database)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taylor, Wendy.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   PC Globe Inc. (products).andO;Product:   PC USA (Geographic information system) (design and construction).andO;Topic:     Software packagesGeography.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>See the U.S.A.andP;  PC USA is geography with a twist.andP;  This hybrid electronicatlas and database from PC Globe combines maps of American states and citieswith demographic and statistical data.andP;  For $69.95, the program is a terrificresearch tool and a marvelous teaching assistant.andM;The atlas portion is straightforward: you simply choose a state or region,and the program brings up a color-selectable map marked with major cities,mountains, forests, and other features.andM;The database is much more intriguing.andP;  It's full of eclectic information onstate population, anticipated growth, migration patterns, number of residentsper doctor, tourist attractions, official state symbols, and so on.andP;  It alsocites statistics on industry, GNP, average income, and crime, among othertopics.andP;  Statistics can be exported to ASCII and Lotus files; graphics can beprinted or captured in a PCX file.andM;It's even more interesting to compare data regarding different states.andP;  Forexample: District of Columbia residents suffer the highest rate of car theft(975 out of 100,000 cars there are stolen), while South Dakotans rest easierwith the lowest (just 99 in 100,000 cars).andP;  You can plot the results of suchresearch on a colorful bar graph or a map of the United States.andM;Because much of the information has a short shelf life, the company plansannual upgrades for $20.andP;  PC Globe can be reached in Tempe, Arizona, at800-255-2789.andO;</TEXT></DOC>